data: {"delta": "**Before you compact the conversation context, any exact tool\u2011output data that still lives only in the chat window must be preserved outside of the transient chat transcript.**  \n\nIn practice this means the following steps should be taken first:\n\n1. **Identify the tool outputs that are still only displayed in the chat.**  \n   - Look for blocks wrapped in `<tool_output \u2026>` (or any other formatting that marks a raw tool response).\n\n2. **Extract the raw data.**  \n   - Copy the entire content of each output (including any tables, JSON, CSV, images encoded as base\u201164, etc.) so that nothing is lost when the chat is trimmed.\n\n3. **Persist the information.**  \n   - Use a persistent storage mechanism (e.g., the `save_memory` tool) to store each output under a clear, retrievable key.  \n   - Optionally, also write the data to an external file or database if the workflow requires it.\n\n4. **Confirm preservation (optional but recommended).**  \n   - Show the user a short summary or a \u201csaved successfully\u201d acknowledgment so they know the information is safe before the context is reduced.\n\n5. **Proceed with context compaction.**  \n   - Once all tool outputs are safely saved, you can safely truncate, summarize, or otherwise compact the chat history without risking loss of the exact raw results.\n\n---\n\n### Why this matters\n- **Data integrity:** Tool outputs often contain the precise numbers, signals, or code results you\u2019ll need for later analysis or audit. Losing them would break reproducibility.\n- **Compliance:** Some regulatory or internal policies require that raw outputs be archived rather than only kept in an ephemeral chat.\n- **Usability:** When you later retrieve the saved memory entries, you\u2019ll have the exact original content\u2014not a paraphrased version\u2014available for verification or further processing.\n\nSo, **the rule is:** *Before any context compaction happens, make sure every tool output that has not yet been persisted is extracted and saved permanently.* This guarantees that no critical information disappears when the chat history is trimmed.", "id": "t1", "type": "text-delta"}

